<span id="v.iii.xvi"></span>

<span id="v.iii.xvi-p1"></span> <span id="page_251">p. 251</span> <span
id="v.iii.xvi-Page_251"></span><span class="c1"><span
id="v.iii.xvi-p1.1"></span>Chapter XVI.—Apostolic Sanction to This
Exclusion of Heretics from the Use of the Scriptures. Heretics,
According to the Apostle, are Not to Be Disputed With, But to Be
Admonished.</span>

<span id="v.iii.xvi-p2"></span>I might be thought to have laid down this
position to remedy distrust in my case, <span
id="fr_2026"></span>[2027](#fn_2026.md) or from a desire of entering on the
contest <span id="fr_2027"></span>[2028](#fn_2027.md) in some other way,
were there not reasons on my side, especially this, that our faith owes
deference <span id="fr_2028"></span>[2029](#fn_2028.md) to the apostle, who
forbids us to enter on “questions,” or to lend our ears to new-fangled
statements, <span id="fr_2029"></span>[2030](#fn_2029.md) or to consort
with a heretic “after the first and second admonition,” <span
id="fr_2030"></span>[2031](#fn_2030) not, (be it observed,.md) after
discussion.  Discussion he has inhibited in this way, by designating
*admonition* as the purpose of dealing with a heretic, and the *first*
one too, because he is not a Christian; in order that he might not,
after the manner of a Christian, seem to require correction again and
again, and “before two or three witnesses,” <span
id="fr_2031"></span>[2032](#fn_2031.md) seeing that he ought to be
corrected, for the very reason that he is not to be disputed with; and
in the next place, because a controversy over the Scriptures can,
clearly, <span id="fr_2032"></span>[2033](#fn_2032.md) produce no other
effect than help to upset either the stomach or the brain.

